  <p>Large image files are one of the biggest culprits behind slow-loading websites. Studies show that a one-second delay in page load time can reduce conversions by up to 7 percent, and images typically account for over half of a web page's total size. The solution is image compression, and when done correctly, you can dramatically reduce file sizes without any visible loss in quality. This guide explains how image compression works and how to do it for free.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Why Image Compression Matters</h2>
  <p>Every time a visitor loads your website, their browser downloads all the images on the page. If those images are unnecessarily large, the page takes longer to render. This affects three critical areas:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Page speed</strong> &mdash; Compressed images load faster, which improves user experience and reduces bounce rates. Google has confirmed that page speed is a ranking factor for both mobile and desktop search results.</li>
    <li><strong>SEO performance</strong> &mdash; Search engines favor fast-loading pages. Optimized images contribute directly to better Core Web Vitals scores, which influence your search rankings.</li>
    <li><strong>Bandwidth and storage</strong> &mdash; Smaller files mean lower hosting costs and less bandwidth usage, which is especially important for sites with high traffic or visitors on mobile data connections.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Lossy vs. Lossless Compression</h2>
  <p>There are two fundamental approaches to image compression, and understanding the difference is key to choosing the right method for your needs.</p>
  <p class="mt-3"><strong>Lossy compression</strong> permanently removes some image data to achieve smaller file sizes. The removed data is typically information the human eye cannot easily detect. JPEG compression is the most common example. At moderate compression levels, the quality difference is virtually imperceptible, but you can achieve file size reductions of 60 to 80 percent.</p>
  <p class="mt-3"><strong>Lossless compression</strong> reduces file size without discarding any data. The original image can be perfectly reconstructed from the compressed file. PNG uses lossless compression by default. The trade-off is that lossless compression produces larger files compared to lossy methods, but there is zero quality degradation.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">JPEG vs. PNG vs. WebP: Which Format Should You Use?</h2>
  <p>Choosing the right image format is just as important as compression itself. Each format has strengths that make it ideal for specific use cases.</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 mt-4">
    <li><strong>JPEG</strong> &mdash; Best for photographs and images with complex colors and gradients. JPEG uses lossy compression and does not support transparency. It is the most widely supported format and produces small file sizes for photographic content.</li>
    <li><strong>PNG</strong> &mdash; Best for graphics, logos, icons, and images that require transparency. PNG uses lossless compression, so it preserves sharp edges and text perfectly. However, PNG files are typically larger than JPEG for photographic content.</li>
    <li><strong>WebP</strong> &mdash; A modern format developed by Google that supports both lossy and lossless compression, as well as transparency. WebP files are typically 25 to 35 percent smaller than equivalent JPEG or PNG files. All major browsers now support WebP, making it an excellent choice for web use.</li>
  </ul>

