  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-4">Tips for Web Image Optimization</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mt-4">
    <li><strong>Resize before compressing</strong> &mdash; If your image is 4000 pixels wide but only displays at 800 pixels on your site, resize it first. There is no point in compressing pixels that will never be seen.</li>
    <li><strong>Use responsive images</strong> &mdash; Serve different image sizes for different screen sizes using the srcset attribute. This ensures mobile users do not download desktop-sized images.</li>
    <li><strong>Consider WebP as your default</strong> &mdash; With universal browser support, WebP offers the best balance of quality and file size for most web content.</li>
    <li><strong>Compress screenshots and diagrams as PNG</strong> &mdash; Content with text, sharp lines, or flat colors compresses better in PNG format than JPEG, which can introduce blurry artifacts around edges.</li>
    <li><strong>Aim for under 200 KB per image</strong> &mdash; For standard web images, keeping each file under 200 KB ensures fast loading without noticeable quality loss.</li>
    <li><strong>Always test visual quality</strong> &mdash; After compressing, zoom in and compare the original and compressed versions side by side. If you can see artifacts or blurriness, increase the quality setting slightly.</li>
  </ul>

